          <text>
            Something drops from the canopy ahead of me.

            I stop dead, heart hammering against my ribs — my hand goes instinctively to the emergency beacon at my belt, though what good that would do—

            ¶

            The thing sits on the groundcover, completely still. It's round — sphere-shaped, maybe the size of a basketball. The surface looks brownish-green and fuzzy, not fur but something plant-like: thin branches or leaves woven tight together. It just sits there in the filtered purple light, utterly motionless — not threatening, just there.

            I stare at it. Does it stare back? There are no eyes visible, but I feel a _presence_ — an awareness.

            I whisper, "Buddy — what am I looking at?"

            Buddy replies, "Scanning now. I'm detecting plant-based organic material, but the locomotion mechanism is—"

            The sphere bounces. Once. A small hop, maybe ten centimeters off the ground.

            I jump back, pain flaring in my leg.

            The sphere bounces again and rolls slightly forward — toward me.

            It's moving _toward_ me.

            I breathe, "Oh shit."

            The sphere — the *plant ball* — bounces closer. Not fast, not aggressive. The movement has a quality like watching a butterfly move: controlled, deliberate. It bounces in a gentle arc, then rolls to a stop, then bounces again.

            Not random. Not mindless. Curious.

            It circles around me at a careful distance. I turn to keep it in view, wincing as my injured leg protests. The plant sphere continues its circuit, observing me from different angles — or at least it feels like observation.

            "Hello?" I try.

            The sphere keeps bouncing. No response. Just that same gentle tumbling movement.

            I ask, "Buddy, is it trying to communicate?"

            Buddy replies, "I'm not receiving any communication signals on standard frequencies. Perhaps it doesn't possess—"

            The plant ball rolls closer, stopping about a meter away. Close enough that I can see the surface isn't smooth — tiny branches shift and reposition themselves like fingers flexing. The whole thing seems to breathe, or pulse, or _something_. Living. Definitely living. And moving with clear purpose.

            My heart is still racing, but it doesn't feel threatening. It feels more like meeting a friendly dog that sniffs you to figure out what you are — curious, investigating.

            I crouch slowly, careful of my injured leg, until I'm closer to the plant's level. "I'm Kira — I crashed here — I don't know if you can understand me, but I'm not trying to hurt anything. I just need water and—"

            The sphere rolls forward, closer, right up to me, examining. It begins to circle me again, but slower this time, deliberate. It stops at my injured leg — the bandage visible through my torn pants — and bounces in place, focused.

            I hold very still.
          </text>
