          <text>
            A small tendril extends from the sphere's surface—thin, delicate, reaching toward my bandage, getting closer.

            My breath catches—the tendril is maybe five centimeters away now, stretching out so carefully, so _gently_—

            I jerk back, scrambling to my feet as pain explodes through my leg; I gasp and grab at the injury.

            The plant ball immediately rolls backward—fast, several meters, then stops.

            It just sits there—not approaching.

            I stand, breathing hard, one hand pressed to my thigh; my heart hammers. It was pure instinct, a pure fear response—something unknown reaching for me and every animal part of my brain screamed _danger_.

            But looking at the sphere now…

            It isn't moving—it backed off the instant I flinched and gave me space.

            It wasn't attacking; it was… concerned? Curious about my injury? Trying to help?

            I say, "I'm sorry—you startled me. I didn't mean to…"

            The plant ball doesn't move; it just sits there, waiting.

            Buddy says, "Kira— I don't think it's hostile. The approach patterns suggest curiosity rather than predatory behavior."

            I say, "I know, I know—it's just…"

            First contact—actual alien first contact—and I flinched away like it was going to hurt me.

            I take a slow breath, crouch down again, and say, "It's okay—you can… I'm okay. I just got scared."

            The sphere hesitates—at least it feels like hesitation—then rolls forward slowly and stops closer this time, still not touching, giving me space.

            We regard each other—no words, no shared language—but _something_ passes between us in that moment; some kind of… recognition?

            The plant is curious—and so am I. We're both trying to figure out what the other is.

            The moment hangs in the purple twilight, in the eerie quiet of the alien forest—human and plant-thing, watching each other.

            Then the sphere suddenly shifts—its whole surface rippling, branches realigning. It orients toward the trees; no eyes, but the direction is unmistakable.

            More movement approaches; I can hear it now—rustling in the canopy, the sound of many things moving through the branches. Others are coming.

            The plant ball bounces once more—a quick little hop that feels like acknowledgment or farewell or _something_—then tumbles away rapidly toward the approaching sounds until it disappears into the purple shadows between the trees.

            ¶

            I stand slowly, breathing hard.

            That was… that was first contact.

            An actual alien life form—a bouncing plant ball that can't talk. And somehow, for just a moment, we understood each other.

            The sounds are getting closer—more rustling, more movement. More of them are coming.

            I straighten, heart pounding again for entirely different reasons.

            Time to find out what else lives on this planet.
          </text>
